CPISAM(1T)						 CPISAM(1T)

NAME
     cpisam - Copies T-ISAM files

SYNOPSIS
     cpisam -v src_data [+src_index] ... dest_data [+dest_index]

DESCRIPTION
   Purpose
     The cpisam utility copies source T-ISAM files to destination
     T-ISAM files.  The path name of the index file is kept in
     the data file's internal information. In some cases, T-ISAM
     uses this internal name to locate the index file. Because
     cpisam updates this internal path name, it should be used
     whenever a T-ISAM file is copied.	Usage of the cp command
     does not update this internal information of the destination
     file, sometimes resulting in the association of the wrong
     index file with the given data file.

   Discussion
     Except for the last parameter, which can be a directory,
     parameters beginning with a + character are taken to be
     names of index files associated with the preceding data file
     name.  In cases where index files are not specified for a
     given data file, the index file normally associated with the
     data file (according to the internal information in the data
     file) is used.  If dest_index is not specified, the index
     file(s) is copied to the same file name as the source index
     file within the dest_data directory, or the directory
     portion of the dest_data path name.

     If dest_data and dest_index (if present) are directories,
     there can be multiple src_data files.  This implies that the
     src_data files copied to the dest_data directory and
     corresponding src_index files are copied to the dest_index
     directory, if it is present. If the dest_index is not
     present, the corresponding src_index files are copied to the
     dest_data directory.  If dest_data is not a directory, there
     can only be one src_data file.

     Copying data and index files to the same location is not
     permitted.

   Options
     -v      Verbose.  Lists to standard output exactly which
	     files are copied where.

EXAMPLES
     The following example copies file1.dat, with its index file to
     the directory dir2.

	       cpisam file1.dat dir2


     The next example copies the T-ISAM file contained in
     file1.dat and file1.idx to file2.dat and file2.idx.

	       cpisam file1.dat +file1.idx file2.dat +file2.idx


     The next example copies the T-ISAM file contained in
     file1.dat and file1.idx to the directory dir2.

	       cpisam file1.dat +file1.idx dir2


     To copy the files f1.dat, f2.dat, and f3.dat, with
     corresponding indexes f1.idx, f2.idx, and f3.idx, to
     directory dir4, type the following command:

	       cpisam f1.dat +f1.idx f2.dat +f2.idx f3.dat +f3.idx dir4


     You must use either of the following forms to ensure that
     the .idx file is copied correctly:

	       cpisam file1.dat file2.dat +file2.idx

			  or

	       cpisam file1.dat +file1.idx file2.dat +file2.idx


PROMPTS
   Source Data File:
     Enter the data portion of the source T-ISAM file.

   Source Index File:
     Optional. Enter the index portion of the source T-ISAM file.

   Destination Data File:
     Enter the data portion of the destination T-ISAM file.

   Destination Index File:
     Optional. Enter the index portion of the destination T-ISAM
     file.

   Verbose? (y/n):
     Enter y to print a list of copied files to the screen.

